Population numbers are given in millions and areas are given in square kilometers. The three different kinds of populations refer to different ways of describing what is included in a city. The feature population is a measurement from the UN (2018) that tries to consistently define the region of a city. More information is available in the U.N.â€™s World Urbanization Prospectus, which is available here. The other three measurements refer to:

  • city: city proper, defined by local administrative boundaries
  • metro: according to UNICEF, the Metro Region is an area â€œcomprising the urban area as a whole and its primary commuter areasâ€¦ In addition to the city proper, a metropolitan area includes both the surrounding territory with urban levels of residential density and some additional lower-density areas that are adjacent to and linked to the city.â€ See UNICEF for more information.
  • urban: an area that consists of a â€œcontinuously built up land mass of urban development that is within a labor market (metropolitan area or metropolitan region) and contains no rural landâ€.

Several of the questions in this and the following notebooks concern the analysis of the relationship between these various definitions.

Scatterplot

In the code below, write the code to produce a scatter plot with population on the x-axis and the city population on the y-axis. I have set warning=FALSE because there are some missing data values and it will be helpful to turn off the warnings about these data rows.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = population, y = city_pop))

Now, in the code region below, produce a scatter plot with population on the x-axis and metro population on the y-axis.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = population, y = metro_pop))

Which of the two regional populations (metro or city) seem to more closely relate to the U.N.â€™s definition of a cities population (e.g., the population feature). Answer: The metropolitan population is much closer to the UN definition than the city population feature

Text Plot

Produce a plot with population on the x-axis and metro population on the y-axis and label each point with the city name.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_text(aes(x = population, y = metro_pop, label = city))

What two cities seem to have the largest (absolute) discrepancy between their UN population and the metro population? Answer: Jakarta and Seoul seem to stand out the most (their metro populations are much larger than the official UN population numbers).

Produce a plot with a text geometry where longitude (lon) is on the x-axis, latitude is on the y-axis (lat), and the labels are given by the city names (name).

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_text(aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = name))

This should roughly resemble a map of the world. In the code below, produce a modified version of this plot, replacing the text layer with two layers: a text repel layer and well as a point layer.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_text_repel(aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = name)) +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat))

Which of these two plots do you find easier to read, and why? (Note, there is no clear correct answer here). Answer: I slightly prefer the second, but it would be better to, perhaps, show only a subset of the labels. We will see how to do this soon!

Make your own tibble!

As a final exercise, we will create a small tabular data set manually and construct a plot on based on it. In the block below, make and save a data set with 4-5 observations and three features: two numeric and one character. Name the object and features following the naming rules we covered; the exact choice is yours.

fav_drinks <- tibble(
  name = c("Tea", "Coffee", "Red Wine", "Gin Martini", "Kombucha"),
  caffeine = c(47, 95, 0, 0, 14),     # in milligrams
  alcohol = c(0, 0, 14, 50, 2)        # percentage
)

Draw a scatter plot with points and text (using geom_text_repel) using your data, with the numeric feature on the x and y-axes and the labels giving the character feature

fav_drinks %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = caffeine, y = alcohol)) +
    geom_text_repel(aes(x = caffeine, y = alcohol, label = name))

Finally, create bar plot using geom_col that shows one of the numeric feature on the y-axis and the categorical feature on the x-axis.

fav_drinks %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_col(aes(x = name, y = caffeine))
